{"title_page": "Albert Heath", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Albert \"Tootie\" Heath\n| image               = Tootie Heath.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Albert \"Tootie\" Heath in 2014\n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Albert Heath\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1935|05|31}}\n| birth_place         = \n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n| years_active        = 1957\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Heath Brothers]]\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Albert''' \"'''Tootie'''\" '''Heath''' (born  May 31, 1935) is an American [[jazz]] [[hard bop]] [[drummer]], the brother of tenor [[saxophonist]] [[Jimmy Heath]] and the [[double-bassist]] [[Percy Heath]].<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p85530/biography|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic]</ref>\n\nHe first recorded in 1957 with [[John Coltrane]]. From 1958 to 1974 he worked with, among others, [[J. J. Johnson]], [[Wes Montgomery]], [[Art Farmer]] and [[Benny Golson]]'s [[Jazztet]], [[Cedar Walton]], [[Bobby Timmons]], [[Kenny Drew]], [[Sonny Rollins]], [[Dexter Gordon]], [[Johnny Griffin]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Friedrich Gulda]], [[Nina Simone]], and [[Yusef Lateef]]. In 1975, he, Jimmy and Percy formed the [[Heath Brothers]].  He remained with the group until 1978, then left to freelance. He has recorded extensively throughout his career.\n\nAmong his many workshop and classroom teaching assignments, Tootie Heath is a regular instructor at the [[Stanford Jazz Workshop]].\n\nTootie Heath is now the producer and leader of The Whole Drum Truth, a jazz drum ensemble featuring [[Ben Riley]], [[Ed Thigpen]], Jackie Williams, [[Billy Hart]], [[Charlie Persip]], [[Leroy Williams]] and [[Louis Hayes]].\n\n==Discography==\n\n===As leader===\n*1969: ''Kawaida'' (O'Be, 1969) with [[Ed Blackwell]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Buster Williams]]\n*1974: ''[[Kwanza (The First)]]'' ([[Muse Records|Muse]])\n*2009: ''Live at Smalls'' (Smalls Live) \n*2012: ''Krakkle'' (Geco)\n*2013: ''Tootie's Tempo'' (Sunnyside) \n*2014: ''Philadelphia Beat'' (Sunnyside)\n\n===As sideman===\n'''With [[Kenny Barron]]'''\n*''[[Peruvian Blue]]'' (Muse, 1974)\n'''With [[Walter Benton]]'''\n*''[[Out of This World (Walter Benton album)|Out of This World]]'' (Jazzland, 1960)\n'''With [[Anthony Braxton]]'''\n*''[[In the Tradition (Anthony Braxton album)|In the Tradition]]'' (SteepleChase, 1974)\n*''[[In the Tradition Volume 2]]'' (SteepleChase, 1974 [1977])\n'''With [[George Cables]]'''\n*''[[Skylark (George Cables album)|Skylark]]'' (SteepleChase, 1995)\n'''With the [[Kenny Clarke/Francy Boland Big Band]]'''\n*''[[Latin Kaleidoscope]]'' (MPS, 1968)\n'''With [[John Coltrane]]'''\n*''[[Coltrane (1957 album)|Coltrane]]'' (Prestige, 1957)\n*''[[Lush Life (John Coltrane album)|Lush Life]]'' (Prestige, 1956-58 [1961])\n'''With [[Ted Curson]]'''\n*''[[Quicksand (Ted Curson album)|Quicksand]]'' (Atlantic, 1974)\n'''With [[Kenny Dorham]]'''\n*''[[Trompeta Toccata]]'' (Blue Note, 1964)\n'''With [[Art Farmer]]'''\n*''[[Big City Sounds]]'' (Argo, 1960) with Benny Golson\n* ''[[Art (album)|Art]]'' (Argo, 1960)\n*''[[The Jazztet and John Lewis]]'' (Argo, 1961) with Benny Golson\n*''[[The Jazztet at Birdhouse]]'' (Argo, 1961) with Benny Golson\n*''[[New York Jazz Sextet: Group Therapy]]'' (Scepter, 1966)\n*''[[Voices All]]'' (Eastworld, 1982) with Benny Golson\n*''[[Moment to Moment (album)|Moment to Moment]]'' (Soul Note, 1983) with Benny Golson\n*''[[Central Avenue Reunion]]'' (Contemporary, 1989)\n'''With [[Benny Golson]]'''\n*''[[Take a Number from 1 to 10]]'' (Argo, 1961)\n*''[[The Roland Kirk Quartet Meets the Benny Golson Orchestra]]'' (Mercury, 1964)\n'''With [[Dexter Gordon]]'''\n*''[[Both Sides of Midnight]]'' ([[Black Lion Records|Black Lion]], 1967 [1981])\n*''[[Body and Soul (Dexter Gordon album)|Body and Soul]]'' (Black Lion, 1967 [1981]) \n*''[[Take the \"A\" Train (Dexter Gordon album)|Take the \"A\" Train]]'' (Black Lion, 1967 [1988]) \n*''[[The Tower of Power!]]'' (Prestige, 1969)\n*''[[More Power!]]'' (Prestige, 1969)\n*''[[The Apartment (album)|The Apartment]]'' (SteepleChase, 1975)\n'''With [[Bennie Green]] and [[Gene Ammons]]'''\n*''[[The Swingin'est]]'' (1958)\n'''With [[Johnny Griffin]]'''\n*''[[Bush Dance (album)|Bush Dance]]'' ([[Galaxy]], 1978)\n'''With [[Herbie Hancock]]'''\n*''[[The Prisoner (album)|The Prisoner]]'' ([[Blue Note]], 1969)\n'''With [[Jimmy Heath]]'''\n*''[[The Thumper]]'' (Riverside, 1959)\n*''[[Really Big!]]'' (Riverside, 1960)\n*''[[The Quota]]'' (Riverside, 1961)\n*''[[Triple Threat (Jimmy Heath album)|Triple Threat]]'' (Riverside, 1962)\n*''[[Swamp Seed]]'' (Riverside, 1963)\n*''[[On the Trail]]'' (Riverside, 1964)\n*''[[The Gap Sealer]]'' (Cobblestone, 1973)\n*''[[You've Changed (album)|You've Changed]]'' (SteepleChase, 1991)\n*''[[You or Me]]'' (SteepleChase, 1995)\n'''With [[Milt Jackson]]'''\n*''[[Milt Jackson Quintet Live at the Village Gate]]'' (Riverside, 1963)\n*''[[Much in Common]]'' with [[Ray Brown (musician)|Ray Brown]] (Verve, 1964)\n'''With [[J. J. Johnson]]'''\n*''[[J. J. in Person!]]'' (Columbia, 1958)\n*''[[Really Livin']]'' (Columbia, 1959)\n*''[[J.J. Inc.]]'' ([[Columbia Records|Columbia]], 1961)\n'''With [[Clifford Jordan]]'''\n*''[[Spellbound (Clifford Jordan album)|Spellbound]]'' (Riverside, 1960)\n*''[[Starting Time]]'' (Jazzland, 1961)\n*''[[These are My Roots: Clifford Jordan Plays Leadbelly]]'' (Atlantic, 1965)\n*''[[In the World]]'' (Strata-East, 1969 [1972])\n*''[[Half Note (album)|Half Note]]'' (SteepleChase, 1974 [1985])\n'''With [[Yusef Lateef]]'''\n*''[[Yusef Lateef's Detroit]]'' ([[Atlantic]], 1969)\n*''[[Suite 16 (album)|Suite 16]]'' (Atlantic, 1970)\n*''[[The Gentle Giant]]'' (Atlantic, 1971)\n*''[[Hush 'N' Thunder]]'' (Atlantic, 1972)\n*''[[Part of the Search]]'' (Atlantic, 1973)\n*''[[10 Years Hence]]'' (Atlantic, 1974)\n'''With [[Johnny Lytle]]'''\n*''[[Blue Vibes]]'' (Jazzland, 1960)\n'''With [[Warne Marsh]]'''\n*''[[Back Home (Warne Marsh album)|Back Home]]'' ([[Criss Cross Jazz]], 1986)\n'''With [[Ronnie Mathews]]'''\n*''[[Doin' the Thang!]]'' (Prestige, 1963)\n'''With [[Charles McPherson (musician)|Charles McPherson]]'''\n*''[[Bebop Revisited!]]'' (Prestige, 1964)\n'''With [[Blue Mitchell]]'''\n*''[[A Sure Thing]]'' (1962)\n*''[[Mapenzi]]'' with [[Harold Land]] (Concord, 1977)\n'''With [[Roscoe Mitchell]]'''\n*''[[Hey Donald]]'' ([[Delmark]], 1995)\n*''[[In Walked Buckner]]'' (Delmark, 1999)\n'''With [[Wes Montgomery]]'''\n*''[[The Incredible Jazz Guitar of Wes Montgomery]]'' (Riverside, 1960)\n'''With [[Tete Montoliu]]'''\n*''[[Piano for Nuria]]'' (SABA, 1968)\n*''[[Catalonian Fire]]'' (SteepleChase, 1974)\n*''[[Tete!]]'' (SteepleChase, 1975)\n*''[[T\u00eate \u00e0 Tete (Tete Montoliu album)|T\u00eate \u00e0 Tete]]'' (SteepleChase, 1976)\n*''[[Tootie's Tempo]]'' (SteepleChase, 1976 [1979])\n*''[[Catalonian Nights Vol. 1]]'' (Steeplechase, 1980 [1981])\n*''[[Catalonian Nights Vol. 2]]'' (Steeplechase, 1980 [1985])\n*''[[Catalonian Nights Vol. 3]]'' (Steeplechase, 1980 [1989])\n'''With [[Don Patterson (organist)|Don Patterson]]'''\n*''[[These Are Soulful Days]]'' ([[Muse Records|Muse]], 1973)\n'''With [[Cecil Payne]]'''\n*''[[Zodiac (Cecil Payne album)|Zodiac]]'' ([[Strata-East]], 1968 [1973])\n'''With [[Niels-Henning Orsted Pedersen]]'''\n*''[[Double Bass (album)|Double Bass]]'' (SteepleChase, 1976) with [[Sam Jones (musician)|Sam Jones]]\n'''With [[Sonny Red]]'''\n*''[[Breezing (album)|Breezing]]'' ([[Jazzland Records (American record label)|Jazzland]], 1960)\n'''With [[George Russell (composer)|George Russell]]'''\n*''[[George Russell Sextet at Beethoven Hall]]'' (1965)\n'''With [[Bud Shank]]'''\n*''[[That Old Feeling (Bud Shank album)|That Old Feeling]]'' ([[Contemporary]], 1986)\n'''With [[Nina Simone]]'''\n*''[[Little Girl Blue (Nina Simone album)|Little Girl Blue]]'' (1958)\n*''[[Nina Simone and Her Friends]]'' (1959)\n'''With [[Billy Taylor]]'''\n*''[[Billy Taylor with Four Flutes]]'' ([[Riverside Records|Riverside]], 1959)\n'''With [[Bobby Timmons]]'''\n*''[[Chun-King]]'' (Prestige, 1964)\n'''With [[Mal Waldron]]'''\n*''[[Impressions (Mal Waldron album)|Impressions]]'' (New Jazz, 1959)\n'''With [[Cedar Walton]]'''\n*''[[Soul Cycle]]'' ([[Prestige Records|Prestige]], 1969)\n'''With [[The Young Lions (band)|The Young Lions]]'''\n*''[[The Young Lions (album)|The Young Lions]]'' ([[Vee-Jay]], 1960)\n'''With [[Michel Sardaby]]'''\n*''Night Blossom'' (Diw Records, 1990)\n'''With Guido Manusardi'''\n*''Trio de Jazz'' (Electrecord \u2013 EDE 0476, 1968)\n'''With [[Kenny Drew]]'''\n*''Dark Beauty'' ([[SteepleChase Records|Steeplechase]], 1974)\n'''With [[Roberto Magris]]:'''\n* ''[[Morgan Rewind: A Tribute to Lee Morgan Vol. 1]]'' ([[JMood Records|JMood]], 2012)\n* ''[[One Night in with Hope and More Vol. 1]]'' (JMood, 2012)\n* ''[[One Night in with Hope and More Vol. 2]]'' (JMood, 2013)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://soulpatchmusicproductions.com/index.php/artists/albert-tootie-heath Tootie Heath biography and management] \n* [http://www.brotherlyjazz.com Brotherly Jazz: The Heath Brothers DVD Documentary]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/tootieheath Tootie Heath's MySpace page]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/04/movies/music-in-review-heath-brothers.html?scp=2&sq=Heath+Brothers&st=nyt Music in Review; Heath Brothers, by Ben Ratliff, New York Times, April 4, 2003]\n* [https://ethaniverson.com/interviews/interview-with-albert-tootie-heath/ DTM interview]\n*[https://www.npr.org/2015/03/14/392324106/albert-tootie-heath-drummer-extraordinaire-turns-the-tables NPR interview]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heath, Albert}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Hard bop drummers]]\n[[Category:Post-bop drummers]]\n[[Category:American jazz drummers]]\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:Jazz musicians from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Muse Records artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American drummers]]\n[[Category:American male drummers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Modern Jazz Quartet members]]\n[[Category:Heath Brothers members]]\n[[Category:The Jazztet members]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Albert \"Tootie\" Heath\n| image               = Tootie Heath.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Albert \"Tootie\" Heath in 2014\n| image_size          = \n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name          = Albert Heath\n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1935|05|31}}\n| birth_place         = \n| origin              = \n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         = \n| genre               = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation          = \n| instrument          = [[Drum kit|Drums]]\n| years_active        = 1957\u2013present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[Heath Brothers]]\n| website             = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n}}\n'''Albert''' \"'''Tootie'''\" '''Heath''' (born  May 31, 1935) is an American [[jazz]] [[hard bop]] [[drummer]], the brother of tenor [[saxophonist]] [[Jimmy Heath]] and the [[double-bassist]] [[Percy Heath]].<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p85530/biography|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic]</ref>\n\nHe first recorded in 1957 with [[John Coltrane]]. From 1958 to 1974 he worked with, among others, [[J. J. Johnson]], [[Wes Montgomery]], [[Art Farmer]] and [[Benny Golson]]'s [[Jazztet]], [[Cedar Walton]], [[Bobby Timmons]], [[Kenny Drew]], [[Sonny Rollins]], [[Dexter Gordon]], [[Johnny Griffin]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Friedrich Gulda]], [[Nina Simone]], and [[Yusef Lateef]]. In 1975, he, Jimmy and Percy formed the [[Heath Brothers]].  He remained with the group until 1978, then left to freelance. He has recorded extensively throughout his career.\n\nAmong his many workshop and classroom teaching assignments, Tootie Heath is a regular instructor at the [[Stanford Jazz Workshop]].\n\nTootie Heath is now the producer and leader of The Whole Drum Truth, a jazz drum ensemble featuring [[Ben Riley]], [[Ed Thigpen]], Jackie Williams, [[Billy Hart]], [[Charlie Persip]], [[Leroy Williams]] and [[Louis Hayes]].\n\n==Discography==\n\n===As leader===\n*1969: ''Kawaida'' (O'Be, 1969) with [[Ed Blackwell]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Buster Williams]]\n*1974: ''[[Kwanza (The First)]]'' ([[Muse Records|Muse]])\n*2009: ''Live at Smalls'' (Smalls Live) \n*2012: ''Krakkle'' (Geco)\n*2013: ''Tootie's Tempo'' (Sunnyside) \n*2014: ''Philadelphia Beat'' (Sunnyside)\n\n===As sideman===\n'''With [[Kenny Barron]]'''\n*''[[Peruvian Blue]]'' (Muse, 1974)\n'''With [[Walter Benton]]'''\n*''[[Out of This World (Walter Benton album)|Out of This World]]'' (Jazzland, 1960)\n'''With [[Anthony Braxton]]'''\n*''[[In the Tradition (Anthony Braxton album)|In the Tradition]]'' (SteepleChase, 1974)\n*''[[In the Tradition Volume 2]]'' (SteepleChase, 1974 [1977])\n'''With [[George Cables]]'''\n*''[[Skylark (George Cables album)|Skylark]]'' (SteepleChase, 1995)\n'''With the [[Kenny Clarke/Francy Boland Big Band]]'''\n*''[[Latin Kaleidoscope]]'' (MPS, 1968)\n'''With [[John Coltrane]]'''\n*''[[Coltrane (1957 album)|Coltrane]]'' (Prestige, 1957)\n*''[[Lush Life (John Coltrane album)|Lush Life]]'' (Prestige, 1956-58 [1961])\n'''With [[Ted Curson]]'''\n*''[[Quicksand (Ted Curson album)|Quicksand]]'