{"title_page": "Tarik Freitekh", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2020}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tarik Freitekh\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e\n| native_name_lang   = Arabic\n| image              = Attachment 180115032013.jpg\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1987|10|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = Jerusalem, Israel\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = California, United States\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Billionaire, Businessman, producer, director\n| organization       = Petronor Oil\n| net_worth          = $4 Billion \u2191\n}}\n\n'''Tarik Freitekh''' {{lang-ar|\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e}}; born 5 October 1987) is an American billionaire, businessman, producer, and director.<ref name=one>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.wilsdomain.com/blog/news/adding-to-an-impressive-celebrity-net-worth-tarik-freitekh-gains-recognition-in-the-music-industry/\n|accessdate=2014-05-13\n|title=Adding to An Impressive Celebrity Net Worth Tarik Freitekh Gains Recognition in the Music Industry\n|newspaper=Wil's Domain Weblog\n|date=April 25, 2014\n}}</ref> \nHe runs his own international distribution company in [[Dubai]], recording studios in [[Hollywood, California]], and video studios in [[Miami, Florida]]. He is also the owner of a number of restaurants and hookah lounges within the United States, and is the co-founder Petronor Oil, CBDPH <ref>https://www.openthenews.com/kourtney-kardashianaes-launches-anti-aging-cbd-from-billionaire-tarik-freitekhaes-largest-cbd-farms/</ref>  <ref>https://timesofcbd.com/kourtney-kardashian-goes-to-mask-cbd-beauty-mask-debut-by-tarik-freitekhs-farms/ </ref> Starbuzz Entertainment and World Music production.\n\n==Early life==\nFreitekh was born October 5, 1987, in [[Jerusalem]]. He obtained two bachelor\u2019s degrees: one from the [[University of Technology, Sydney]] in architecture, and the other from the Art Institute, a bachelor of arts in digital filmmaking.<ref name=\"one\"/>\n\n==Career==\nFreitekh's music label signed the Arab diva [[Haifa Wehbe]], one of the Middle East's most famous singers and actresses.<ref name=three>{{cite news\n\n|url=http://chababs.com/\u0645\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0642\u0649/15077/\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621-\u0648\u0647\u0628\u064a-\u0641\u064a-\u0639\u0645\u0644-\u0645\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u064a\u0627\u0631-\u0627\u0644\u062b\u0642\u064a\u0644-\u0645\u0639-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062e\u0631\u062c-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a-\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642-\u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e\n\n|accessdate=2014-05-28\n|title=Haifa Wehbe works with \"high-caliber\" global director Tareq Freitekh\n|newspaper=Chabab\n|date=February 5, 2014\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref> Also, in 2014, the Cuban singer [[Nayer]] signed with his label; she is known for her hit songs with [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] (\"Pearly Gates\", \"Sauvamente\") and [[Ne-Yo]] (\"Give Me Everything\"). He recently finished directing a music video for the rap artist [[Snoop Dogg]] plus previous projects with [[Shakira]], [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy]], [[R. Kelly]], [[Tamer Hosny]], and [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref name=four>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.lebanonfiles.com/news/635841\n|accessdate=2014-05-27\n|title=Tariq Freitekh combines Akon Jennifer Lopez\n|newspaper=Lebanon Files\n|date=November 29, 2013\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref>\nFreitekh also received the award for best director at the Los Angeles Festival of Music for the song \"Cherokee\" in 2012.<ref name=five>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.masress.com/elsaba7/65481\n\n|accessdate=2014-05-27\n|title=Global Director Tarik Freitekh Discovers Talented International Singers\n|newspaper=Masress\n|date=January 1, 2013\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref><ref name=six>{{cite news\n |url         = http://la.lifediverse.com/tarik-freitekh-wins-best-director-at-music-video-film-festival/\n |accessdate  = 2014-05-27\n |title       = Tarik Freitekh Wins Best Director at Music Video Film Festival\n |newspaper   = LA Life Magazine\n |date        = August 10, 2012\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140528045720/http://la.lifediverse.com/tarik-freitekh-wins-best-director-at-music-video-film-festival/\n |archivedate = May 28, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFreitekh owns a number of real estate in [[Dubai]], Europe, and the US, including a three-floor mansion in Hollywood Hills sold to him for $7 million and a penthouse in [[Miami]], bought for $2.3 million in 2012. In December 2017, Freitekh was honored as a goodwill ambassador by the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/rahejaweb/goodwill-ambassador-is-a-person-who-advocate-2y1pw|title=Goodwill Ambassador|website=Buzzfeed.com|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goknews.com/goodwill-ambassador/|title=Goodwill Ambassador - Gok News|date=12 December 2017|website=GokNews.com|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe also has a large exotic car collection, in California, including a white Ferrari Italia 2020, white Lamborghini Hurcan Spyder 2020, Black Bentley 2020, and a C63 Black Series 2019.<ref name=one/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freitekh, Tarik}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Palestinian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2020}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tarik Freitekh\n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e\n| native_name_lang   = Arabic\n| image              = Attachment 180115032013.jpg\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1987|10|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = Jerusalem, Israel\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| residence          = California, United States\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Billionaire, Businessman, producer, director\n| organization       = Petronor Oil\n| net_worth          = $4 Billion \u2191\n}}\n\n'''Tarik Freitekh''' {{lang-ar|\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642 \u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e}}; born 5 October 1987) is an American billionaire, businessman, producer, and director.<ref name=one>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.wilsdomain.com/blog/news/adding-to-an-impressive-celebrity-net-worth-tarik-freitekh-gains-recognition-in-the-music-industry/\n|accessdate=2014-05-13\n|title=Adding to An Impressive Celebrity Net Worth Tarik Freitekh Gains Recognition in the Music Industry\n|newspaper=Wil's Domain Weblog\n|date=April 25, 2014\n}}</ref> \nHe runs his own international distribution company in [[Dubai]], recording studios in [[Hollywood, California]], and video studios in [[Miami, Florida]]. He is also the owner of a number of restaurants and hookah lounges within the United States, and is the co-founder of Starbuzz Entertainment and World Music production.\n\n==Early life==\nFreitekh was born October 5, 1987, in [[Jerusalem]]. He obtained two bachelor\u2019s degrees: one from the [[University of Technology, Sydney]] in architecture, and the other from the Art Institute, a bachelor of arts in digital filmmaking.<ref name=\"one\"/>\n\n==Career==\nFreitekh's music label signed the Arab diva [[Haifa Wehbe]], one of the Middle East's most famous singers and actresses.<ref name=three>{{cite news\n\n|url=http://chababs.com/\u0645\u0648\u0633\u064a\u0642\u0649/15077/\u0647\u064a\u0641\u0627\u0621-\u0648\u0647\u0628\u064a-\u0641\u064a-\u0639\u0645\u0644-\u0645\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u064a\u0627\u0631-\u0627\u0644\u062b\u0642\u064a\u0644-\u0645\u0639-\u0627\u0644\u0645\u062e\u0631\u062c-\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a-\u0637\u0627\u0631\u0642-\u0641\u0631\u064a\u062a\u062e\n\n|accessdate=2014-05-28\n|title=Haifa Wehbe works with \"high-caliber\" global director Tareq Freitekh\n|newspaper=Chabab\n|date=February 5, 2014\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref> Also, in 2014, the Cuban singer [[Nayer]] signed with his label; she is known for her hit songs with [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]] (\"Pearly Gates\", \"Sauvamente\") and [[Ne-Yo]] (\"Give Me Everything\"). He recently finished directing a music video for the rap artist [[Snoop Dogg]] plus previous projects with [[Shakira]], [[Shaggy (musician)|Shaggy]], [[R. Kelly]], [[Tamer Hosny]], and [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref name=four>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.lebanonfiles.com/news/635841\n|accessdate=2014-05-27\n|title=Tariq Freitekh combines Akon Jennifer Lopez\n|newspaper=Lebanon Files\n|date=November 29, 2013\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref>\nFreitekh also received the award for best director at the Los Angeles Festival of Music for the song \"Cherokee\" in 2012.<ref name=five>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.masress.com/elsaba7/65481\n\n|accessdate=2014-05-27\n|title=Global Director Tarik Freitekh Discovers Talented International Singers\n|newspaper=Masress\n|date=January 1, 2013\n|language=Arabic\n}}</ref><ref name=six>{{cite news\n |url         = http://la.lifediverse.com/tarik-freitekh-wins-best-director-at-music-video-film-festival/\n |accessdate  = 2014-05-27\n |title       = Tarik Freitekh Wins Best Director at Music Video Film Festival\n |newspaper   = LA Life Magazine\n |date        = August 10, 2012\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140528045720/http://la.lifediverse.com/tarik-freitekh-wins-best-director-at-music-video-film-festival/\n |archivedate = May 28, 2014\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFreitekh owns a number of real estate in [[Dubai]], Europe, and the US, including a three-floor mansion in Hollywood Hills sold to him for $7 million and a penthouse in [[Miami]], bought for $2.3 million in 2012. In December 2017, Freitekh was honored as a goodwill ambassador by the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/rahejaweb/goodwill-ambassador-is-a-person-who-advocate-2y1pw|title=Goodwill Ambassador|website=Buzzfeed.com|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://goknews.com/goodwill-ambassador/|title=Goodwill Ambassador - Gok News|date=12 December 2017|website=GokNews.com|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe also has a large exotic car collection, in California, including a white Ferrari Italia 2020, white Lamborghini Hurcan Spyder 2020, Black Bentley 2020, and a C63 Black Series 2019.<ref name=one/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Freitekh, Tarik}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Palestinian descent]]\n", "name_user": "NatePBillington", "label": "safe", "comment": "organization founder", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tarik_Freitekh"}
{"title_page": "Erivan Province (Safavid Empire)", "text_new": "{{Infobox country\n|conventional_long_name = \n|native_name = Vel\u0101yat-e Irav\u0101n<br>Chokhur-e Sa'd\n|common_name = Iravan\n|government_type  = [[Velayat]]\n|life_span    = 1502\u20131736\n|era          = \n|status       = Province of the [[Safavid Iran|Safavid Empire]]\n|p1           = \n|flag_p1      = \n|p2           =\n|flag_p2      = \n|s1           = Afsharid dynasty\n|flag_s1      = Nader_Shah_Flag.svg\n|s2           = \n|flag_s2      = \n|image_coat   = \n|image_flag   = \n|image_map    = \n|image_map_caption  =\n|national_motto   = \n|national_anthem  = \n|capital          = Erivan ([[Yerevan]])\n|common_languages = [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]], [[Armenian language|Armenian]]\n|currency         = \n|title_leader = ''[[beglarbeg]]'', ''hakem''\n|leader1      = \n|leader2      = \n|title_deputy = \n|deputy1      = \n|deputy2      = \n|stat_area3 = \n|stat_pop1 =\n|today={{flag|Armenia}}<br>{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br>{{flag|Iran}}<br>{{flag|Turkey}}\n}}\nThe '''Erivan Province'''{{efn|Also spelled as the \"Iravan Province\", \"Erevan Province\", or \"Yerevan Province\".}} ({{lang-fa|\u0648\u0644\u0627\u06cc\u062a \u0627\u06cc\u0631\u0648\u0627\u0646|translit=Vel\u0101yat-e Irav\u0101n}}), also known as '''Chokhur-e Sa'd'''{{efn|Also spelled as \"Chukhur-e Sa'd\", \"Chukhur Sa'd\", \"Chukhur-i(-)Sa'd\", or \"Chughur-i Sa'd\". The comparable administrative entity of the [[Zand dynasty|Zand]] and [[Qajar dynasty|Qajar]] era, known as the [[Erivan Khanate]], was also alternatively known as \"Chokhur-e Sa'd\".}} ({{lang-fa|\u0686\u062e\u0648\u0631 \u0633\u0639\u062f|links=no}}), was a ''[[wilayah|velayat]]'' (province) of the [[Safavid Empire]], centered on the territory of the present-day [[Armenia]]. Erivan ([[Yerevan]]) was the provincial capital and the seat of the Safavid governors.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=171}}\n\nAt the end of the Safavid period, it had the following administrative jurisdictions; [[Do\u011fubayaz\u0131t|Bayazid]], Maghazberd, [[Maku, Iran|Maku]], [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic|Nakhchivan]], [[Sadarak Rayon|Sadarak]], Shadidlu, Zaruzbil, and the tribal district of the [[Donboli]]s.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=171}}\n\nThe provinces of Erivan and [[Safavid Qarabagh|Qarabagh]] were the two administrative territories that made up [[Iranian Armenia (1502-1828)|Iranian Armenia]].{{sfn|Bournoutian|2006|page=213}}{{sfn|Payaslian|2007|page=107}}\n\n==History==\nThe alternate name of the province, ''Chokhur-e Sa'd'', had been in use since the fourteenth century.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=170}} The name is derived from a certain Amir Sa'd, the leader of the Turkic Sa'dlu tribe, who had accompanied [[Timur]] from Central Asia.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=170}}{{sfn|Bournoutian|1992|page=2}} The Sa'dlu's had become prominent under their leader, Amir Sa'd, and settled in the Erivan area, where Amir Sa'd became the governor of the area.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=170}}{{sfn|Bournoutian|1992|page=2}} ''Chokhur-e Sa'd'' literally means \"Vale of Sa'd\".{{sfn|Bournoutian|1992|page=2}}\n\nHistoric [[Greater Armenia|Armenia]], which included the territory of the Erivan Province, made part of the Safavid Empire from its earliest days.{{sfn|Floor|2008|pages=171, 299}} In 1502, the first governor of the Erivan Province was appointed by then incumbent King (''[[Shah]]'') [[Ismail I]] ({{reign}}1501\u20131524), and royal Safavid edicts make mention of the province as early as 1505 and 1506.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=171}} As a result of the [[Peace of Amasya]] of 1555, the Safavids, then under King [[Tahmasp I]] ({{reign}}1524\u20131576) were forced to cede the [[Western Armenia|western part of historic Armenia]] to the expanding [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]].{{sfn|Rayfield|2013|page=171}}\n\nIn 1578, the Ottomans [[Ottoman-Safavid War (1578-1590)|invaded]] the Safavid Empire, and by 1583 they were in possession of the Erivan province.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=171}} In 1604, Safavid King [[Abbas I of Persia|Abbas I]] ({{reign}}1588\u20131629) expelled them and re-established the Safavid sway.{{sfn|Imber|2012|page=92}}\n\nAround the same time, realizing the vulnerability of the province, King Abbas I ordered for the mass deportation and relocation of the [[Armenians]] from his [[Iranian Armenia (1502-1828)|Armenian territories]] (which thus included the Erivan Province), deeper into mainland Iran.\n\nAt the beginning of the seventeenth century, some 19,000 converted Catholic Armenians were living in three towns and twelve villages in the [[Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic|Nakhchivan]], [[Alinja|Ernjak]] and Jahuk regions, and had ten Catholic churches to serve them.{{sfn|Kostikyan|2012|page=374}} When the Safavid Empire started to decline, in the second half of the 17th century, during the reign of King [[Suleiman I of Persia|Suleiman I]] (1666\u20131694), the situation of the Catholic Armenians of Nakhchivan deteriorated.{{sfn|Kostikyan|2012|page=374}} As a result of the increasing religious intolerance and misrule by governmental officials, the majority of the Armenian Catholics of Nakchivan had to convert to Islam.{{sfn|Kostikyan|2012|page=374}} The remaining minority either returned to the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]], or migrated to [[Smyrna]], [[Constantinople]], [[Bursa]] and other towns in the [[Ottoman Empire]].{{sfn|Kostikyan|2012|page=374}}\n[[File:Safavid coin struck at the Erivan mint.jpg|thumb|right|Silver coin of Shah [[Sultan Husayn]] ({{reign}}1694\u20131722), struck at the Erivan mint, dated 1702]]\n\nIn 1639, the Safavids and the Ottomans concluded the [[Treaty of Zuhab]]. Eastern Armenia was reconfirmed as being an Iranian domain, whereas Western Armenia was irrevocably lost to the Ottomans. The ensuing period following 1639 was marked by peace and prosperity in the province. At the end of the seventeenth century, the Erivan Province had become a centre of Catholic missionary activities in the empire.{{sfn|Kostikyan|2012|page=374}}\n\nIn 1679, the province was the epicenter of [[1679 Armenia earthquake|an earthquake]], which resulted in the destruction and damaging of numerous notable structures.\n\nIn 1714, the mayor (''kalantar'') of the provincial capital, [[Mohammad Reza Beg]], was appointed as the new ambassador to France, and led the [[Persian embassy to Louis XIV|embassy to Louis XIV]] of 1715.{{sfn|Floor|Herzig|2012|page=312}}\n\nIn 1724, the Ottomans and the [[Russian Empire|Russians]] invaded the crumbling empire. By the [[Treaty of Constantinople (1724)]], they agreed to divide the conquered territories between them. Per the treaty, the Ottomans gained the territory of the Erivan Province.{{sfn|Mikaberidze|2011|page=762}}\n\nBy 1735, [[Nader Shah|Nader-Qoli Beg]] (later known as [[Nader Shah]]) had restored the Safavid sway over the [[Caucasus]], including the Erivan Province. In 1736, he deposed the Safavids and became king himself, establishing the [[Afsharid dynasty]].\n\n==Mint==\nThe provincial capital, Erivan, housed an important Safavid mint. It was one of the few Safavid mints, alongside the ones at [[Tabriz]] and [[Tiflis]] (Tbilisi), where re-minting took place.{{sfn|Matthee|Floor|Clawson|2013|page=53}}\n\n==Stationed Safavid force==\nThe Erivan Province was of high importance to the Safavids, partly due to the fact that it bordered the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Floor|2008|page=171}} The French missionary and traveller P\u00e8re Sanson, who was in the Safavid Empire during the latter part of King [[Suleiman I of Persia|Suleiman I]]'s reign (1666\u20131694), wrote that some 12,000 Safavid troops were stationed in the Erivan Province.{{sfn|Floor|2001|page=212}}\n\n==Religious and ethnic affiliation==\nMuslims constituted majorities in the province, whereas ethnic [[Armenians]] were a minority.{{sfn|Bournoutian|1980|pages=11, 13\u201314}} Until the mid-fourteenth century, Armenians had constituted a majority in [[Eastern Armenia]].{{sfn|Bournoutian|1980|pages=11, 13-14}} \nAt the close of the fourteenth century, after [[Timur]]'s campaigns, Islam had become the dominant faith, and Armenians became a minority in Eastern Armenia.{{sfn|Bournoutian|1980|pages=11, 13-14}}\n\n==List of governors==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  width=\"50%\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFDEAD\"\n! width=\"25%\" | Date\n! width=\"75%\" | Governor\n|-\n|1502-? || Qaracheh-Elyas Beybordlu\n|-\n|1509-?|| Amir Beg Mowsellu Torkman\n|-\n|1514-? || Hamzeh Beg, son of Hoseyn Beg Laleh Ustajlu\n|-\n|1516-1527 || [[Div Sultan Rumlu]]\n|-\n|1527 || Soleyman Beg Rumlu\n|-\n|1549-1550 || Hoseyn Khan Soltan Rumlu\n|-\n|1551-1568 || Shahqoli Soltan Ustajlu, son of Hamzeh Soltan Qazaq\n|-\n|1568-1575 || [[Tokhmaq Khan Ustajlu]]\n|-\n|1575-1576 || Abu Torab Soltan\n|-\n|1576-1577 || Khalil Khan Afshar\n|-\n|1578-1583 || [[Tokhmaq Khan Ustajlu]]\n|-\n|1583-1604 || [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] occupation\n|-\n|1604-1625 || Amir Guneh Khan Aghcheh-Qoyunlu Qajar (aka Saru Aslan)\n|-\n|1625-1635 || Tahmasp Ali Khan Aghcheh-Qoyunlu Qajar (aka ''Shir-bacheh'')\n|-\n|1635-1636 || Ottoman occupation\n|-\n|1636-1639 || Kalb Ali Khan Afshar \n|-\n|1639-1648 || Mohammadqoli [Beg] Khan Chaghatay<br>(aka Chaghatay Kotuk Mohammad Khan)\n|-\n|1648-1653 || Kaykhosrow Khan Cherkes\n|-\n|1654-1656 || [[Mohammad-Qoli Khan of Yerevan|Mohammadqoli Khan]]\n|-\n|1656-1663 || [[Najafqoli Khan Cherkes]]\n|-\n|1663-1666 || Abbasqoli Khan Qajar (son of Amir Guneh Khan)\n|-\n|1666-1674 || [[Safi Khan Lezgi]]\n|-\n|1674 || Saru Khan Beg (interim governor)\n|-\n|1674-1679 || [[Safiqoli Khan (son of Rustam Khan)|Safiqoli Khan]]\n|-\n|1679-1688 || Zal Khan\n|-\n|1690-1693 || Mohammadqoli Khan\n|-\n|1693 || Farz Ali Khan\n|-\n|1695-1698 || Allahqoli Khan\n|-\n|1700 || Farz Ali Khan\n|-\n|1704 || Mohammad Khan\n|-\n|1705 || Abd ol-Masud Khan\n|-\n|?-1716 || [[Mohammad-Ali Khan (sepahsalar)|Mohammad-Ali Khan]]\n|-\n|1716-? || Unnamed son of the predecessor\n|-\n|1719-1723 || Mehr-Ali Khan\n|-\n|1723 || [[Constantine II of Kakheti|Mahmadqoli Khan]]\n|-\n|1724-1735 || Ottoman occupation\n|-\n|1735-1736 || Safavid hegemony restored by [[Nader Shah|Nader-Qoli Beg]] (later known as [[Nader Shah]])\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite journal|last1=Bournoutian|first1=George A.|title=The Population of Persian Armenia Prior to and Immediately Following its Annexation to the Russian Empire: 1826-1832|date=1980|publisher=The Wilson Center, Kennan Institute for Advanced Russian Studies|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Bournoutian|first1=George A.|title=The Khanate of Erevan Under Qajar Rule: 1795-1828|date=1992|series=Persian Studies Series|publisher=Mazda Publishers|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Bournoutian|first1=George A.|title=A Concise History of the Armenian People|date=2006|publisher=Mazda Publishers|location=Costa Mesa, California|isbn=1-56859-141-1|edition=5|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof00geor}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Floor|first1=Willem|title=Safavid Government Institutions|date=2001|publisher=Mazda Publishers|location=Costa Mesa, California|isbn=978-1568591353|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Floor|first1=Willem M.|title=Titles and Emoluments in Safavid Iran: A Third Manual of Safavid Administration, by Mirza Naqi Nasiri|date=2008|publisher=Mage Publishers|location=Washington, DC|isbn=978-1933823232|pages=1\u2013337|ref = harv}} \n* {{cite book|title=Iran and the World in the Safavid Age|publisher=I.B. Tauris|year=2012|isbn=978-1780769905|ref=harv| editor-given1 = Willem | editor-surname1 = Floor | editor-given2 = Edmund | editor-surname2 = Herzig | editor-link2 = Edmund Herzig | postscript = .}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kostikyan|first=Kristine|chapter=European Catholic Missionary Propaganda among the Armenian Population of Safavid Iran|title=Iran and the World in the Safavid Age|publisher=I.B.Tauris|year=2012|isbn=978-1780769905|ref=harv|