e signs law granting himself special powers to address coronavirus outbreak|date=March 25, 2020|work=Rappler|accessdate=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Duterte signs\">{{cite news|last=Aguilar|first=Krissy|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247988/duterte-signs-law-granting-him-special-powers-vs-covid-19|title=Duterte signs law on special powers vs COVID-19|date=March 25, 2020|work=Inquirer|access-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**Eighty-four new cases were confirmed on March 25, surpassing the 600-mark and totaling 636 cases. They also confirmed six new recoveries and three new deaths, bringing the death toll to 38 and recovered patients to 26.<ref name=\":0a\" />\n*March 26\n**The first case of COVID-19 in Zambales was confirmed on March 26.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Aglibot |first1=Joanna Rose |title=Retired US navy man is 1st COVID-19 case of Zambales |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248835/retired-us-navy-man-is-1st-covid-19-case-of-zambales |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |date=March 26, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n**Seventy-one new cases were confirmed on March 26, surpassing the 700-mark and totaling 707 cases. They also confirmed two new recoveries and seven new deaths, bringing the death toll to 45 and recovered patients to 28.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ornedo|first1=Julia Mari|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731396/philippines-covid-19-cases-up-to-707-death-toll-up-to-45/story/|title=Philippines' COVID-19 cases up to 707, death toll now at 45|date=March 26, 2020|work=GMA News Online|accessdate=March 26, 2020|url-status=live|publisher=}}</ref>\n*March 27\n**The first case in Oriental Mindoro was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Galvez|first=Daphne|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249321/oriental-mindoro-first-covid-19-case|title=1 year-old is first COVID-19 patient in Oriental Mindoro|date=March 27, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**Ninety-six new cases were confirmed on March 27, surpassing the 800-mark and totaling 803 cases. They also confirmed three new recoveries and nine new deaths, bringing the death toll to 54 and recovered patients to 31.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Philippines reports 803 COVID-19 cases, 54 deaths |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731558/philippines-reports-803-covid-19-cases-54-deaths/story/ |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sabillo|first=Kristine|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/27/20/covid-19-cases-in-philippines-now-at-803-death-toll-at-54|title=COVID-19 cases in Philippines now at 803, death toll at 54|date=March 27, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**The first case in Bicol was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ostria|first=Rey Anthony|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249675/bicol-ends-covid-19-free-streak-with-3-patients-positive-for-disease|title=Bicol ends COVID-19-free streak with 3 patients positive for disease|date=March 27, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|access-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* March 28\n**The first case in Davao Oriental was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/28/20/city-of-mati-in-davao-oriental-logs-first-cases-of-covid-19|title=City of Mati in Davao Oriental logs first cases of COVID-19|date=Mar 28, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=Mar 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**Two hundred seventy-two new cases on March 28 was confirmed, the number leaped both the 900 and 1000th mark, bringing the COVID-19 cases in the Philippines to 1,075. Fourteen new deaths and four new recoveries were also confirmed, bringing the death toll to 68 and recovered patients to 35.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rey|first=Aika|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256218-coronavirus-cases-philippines-march-28-2020|title=New PH coronavirus cases spike by 272, total now at 1,075|date=Mar 28, 2020|work=Rappler|access-date=Mar 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/28/20/philippines-covid-19-cases-cross-1000-as-doh-announces-272-new-cases|title=Philippines' COVID-19 cases cross 1,000 as DOH confirms 272 new patients|date=March 28, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Marquez|first=Consuelo|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250044/1075-people-in-ph-has-coronavirus-disease-doh|title=BREAKING: 1,075 people in PH has coronavirus disease \u2013 DOH|date=March 28, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|access-date=March 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Philippines reports 14 new COVID-19 deaths as cases breach 1,000 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/731694/philippines-reports-14-new-covid-19-deaths-272-new-cases/story/ |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n*March 29\n**Three hundred forty-three new cases on March 29 was confirmed, bringing the COVID-19 cases in the country to 1,418. Three new deaths and seven new patients recovered, bringing the death toll to 71 and recovered patients to 42.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/29/20/doh-announces-343-new-covid-19-cases-total-now-at-1418|title=DOH announces 343 new COVID-19 cases; total now at 1,418|date=March 29, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*March 30\n**The first cases in [[Zamboanga del Sur]], [[Misamis Occidental]], and [[Lanao del Norte]] were confirmed. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/regional/2020/3/30/Zamboanga-del-Sur-first-coronavirus-cases.html|title=Zamboanga del Sur reports first two COVID-19 cases|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250574/mayor-confirms-first-covid-19-case-in-ozamiz-city|title=Mayor confirms first COVID-19 case in Ozamiz City|last=Agonoy|first=Leah|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/03/covid-10-infected-man-who-joins-davao-derby-triggers-lockdown-in-lanao-village/|title=COVID-19 infected man who joins Davao derby triggers lockdown in Lanao village|last=Umel|first=RIchel V.|date=2020-03-30|website=MindaNews|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n**One hundred twenty-eight new cases on March 30 was confirmed, bringing the COVID-19 cases in the country to 1,546. Seven new deaths and no new recovered patients, bringing the death to 78 and recovered patients to 42.\n*March 31\n**The first case in [[Samar (province)|Samar]], a resident of [[Calbayog|Calbayog City]], was confirmed. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/regional/2020/3/31/calbayog-city-samar-covid-19.html|title=Samar province reports first COVID-19 case in Calbayog City|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n**The first case in [[Ilocos Norte]] was confirmed. All provinces in the [[Ilocos Region]] now have confirmed cases of COVID-19. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/31/angono-dagupan-ilocos-norte-report-first-coronavirus-cases.html|title=Angono, Dagupan, and Ilocos Norte report first COVID-19 cases|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n**Five hundred thirty-eight new cases on March 30 was confirmed, the number leaped the 2000th mark, bringing the COVID-19 cases in the Philippines to 2,084. The death toll is at 88 and recovered patients at 49.\n\n== April ==\n\n* April 1\n** Two hundred twenty-seven new cases on April 1 were confirmed, bringing the COVID-19 cases in the country to 2,311. Out of these cases there were eight new patients who have died and one new patient who have recovered. The death toll is at 96 and recovered patients at 50.\n**Protesters demanding food aid were arrested by Quezon City police.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1252199/qcpd-rounds-up-20-protesters-demanding-for-food-aid|title=QCPD rounds up 20 protesters demanding food aid from gov\u2019t|last=Marquez|first=Consuelo|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n**President Duterte ordered soldiers to shoot protesters and quarantine violators<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/256705-duterte-orders-troops-shoot-kill-coronavirus-quarantine-violators|title='Shoot them dead': Duterte orders troops to kill quarantine violators|last=Tomacruz|first=Sofia|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1252574/duterte-tells-public-wait-for-distribution-of-assistance-dont-use-force|title=Duterte tells public: Wait for distribution of aid, don\u2019t use force|last=Esguerra|first=Darryl John|publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 in the Philippines]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "HueMan1", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_the_2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_Philippines"}
{"title_page": "Colin Vereker, 8th Viscount Gort", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n'''Colin Leopold Prendergast \"Kim\" Vereker, 8th Viscount Gort''', [[Justice of the Peace|JP]] (21 June 1916 \u2013 6 April 1995) was an [[Irish peer]] and member of the [[House of Keys]].\n\n==Life==\nGort was the son of [[Leopold George Prendergast Vereker]] and [[Helen Marjorie Campbell]], and the grandson of the Hon. [[Foley Charles Prendergast Vereker]], the second son of the [[Standish Vereker, 4th Viscount Gort|fourth Viscount]]. He was educated at [[Sevenoaks School]] in [[Kent]]. He joined the [[Royal Navy Volunteer Reserve]] and fought in [[World War II]], rising to the rank of [[Lieutenant-Commander]] and being [[Mentioned in Despatches]].<ref name=burkes>Charles Mosley, editor, [[Burke's Peerage|Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage]], 107th edition, 3 volumes (Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003), volume 2, page 1606</ref> He was a director of Royal Skandia IoM, Invesco Fund Managers IoM, Euronav IoM and Eurofish IoM.\n\nIn 1962 Gort was a [[Justice of the Peace]] for [[Castletown, Isle of Man|Castletown]] in the [[Isle of Man]]. Between 1966 and 1971 he was a Member of the [[House of Keys]] (MHK), the lower house of the [[Tynwald|Parliament of the Isle of Man]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tynwald.org.im/keys/1417-chronological.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-12 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723100305/http://www.tynwald.org.im/keys/1417-chronological.shtml |archivedate=23 July 2008 |df=dmy-all }} Chronological list of Tynwald Members from 1417</ref> He succeeded to the title of [[Viscount Gort]] and Baron Kiltarton of Gort on the death of his first cousin once removed, [[Standish Robert Gage Prendergast Vereker, 7th Viscount Gort|Standish Vereker, 7th Viscount Gort]], in 1975.<ref name=burkes/>\n\nHe married Bettine Mary Mackenzie Green, on 4 July 1946.<ref name=burkes/> Gort died in 1995 aged 78.\n\nThe titles passed to his son [[Foley Vereker]], the ninth Viscount, who also lives on the Isle of Man.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://thepeerage.com/p24104.htm Vereker on the Peerage.com website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080723100305/http://www.tynwald.org.im/keys/1417-chronological.shtml Chronological list of Tynwald Members from 1417]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Standish Vereker, 7th Viscount Gort|Standish Vereker]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Viscount Gort]] |creation=1st creation |years=1975\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Foley Vereker, 9th Viscount Gort|Foley Vereker]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gort, Colin Vereker, 8th Viscount}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sevenoaks School]]\n[[Category:English people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Manx politicians]]\n[[Category:Schuyler family]]\n[[Category:Justices of the peace]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n'''Colin Leopold Prendergast \"Kim\" Vereker, 8th Viscount Gort''', [[Justice of the Peace|JP]] (21 June 1916 \u2013 6 April 1995) was an [[Irish peer]] and member of the [[House of Keys]].\n\n==Life==\nGort was the son of Leopold George Prendergast Vereker and Helen Marjorie Campbell, and the grandson of the Hon. Foley Charles Prendergast Vereker, the second son of the [[Standish Vereker, 4th Viscount Gort|fourth Viscount]]. He was educated at [[Sevenoaks School]] in [[Kent]]. He joined the [[Royal Navy Volunteer Reserve]] and fought in [[World War II]], rising to the rank of Lieutenant-Commander and being [[Mentioned in Despatches]].<ref name=burkes>Charles Mosley, editor, [[Burke's Peerage|Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knightage]], 107th edition, 3 volumes (Wilmington, Delaware, U.S.A.: Burke's Peerage (Genealogical Books) Ltd, 2003), volume 2, page 1606</ref> He was a director of Royal Skandia IoM, Invesco Fund Managers IoM, Euronav IoM and Eurofish IoM.\n\nIn 1962 Gort was a [[Justice of the Peace]] for [[Castletown, Isle of Man|Castletown]] in the [[Isle of Man]]. Between 1966 and 1971 he was a Member of the [[House of Keys]] (MHK), the lower house of the [[Tynwald|Parliament of the Isle of Man]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tynwald.org.im/keys/1417-chronological.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-11-12 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080723100305/http://www.tynwald.org.im/keys/1417-chronological.shtml |archivedate=23 July 2008 |df=dmy-all }} Chronological list of Tynwald Members from 1417</ref> He succeeded to the title of [[Viscount Gort]] and Baron Kiltarton of Gort on the death of his first cousin once removed, [[Standish Robert Gage Prendergast Vereker, 7th Viscount Gort|Standish Vereker, 7th Viscount Gort]], in 1975.<ref name=burkes/>\n\nHe married Bettine Mary Mackenzie Green, on 4 July 1946.<ref name=burkes/> Gort died in 1995 aged 78.\n\nThe titles passed to his son Foley Vereker, the ninth Viscount, who also lives on the Isle of Man.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://thepeerage.com/p24104.htm Vereker on the Peerage.com website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080723100305/http://www.tynwald.org.im/keys/1417-chronological.shtml Chronological list of Tynwald Members from 1417]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-bef |before=[[Standish Vereker, 7th Viscount Gort|Standish Vereker]]}}\n{{s-ttl |title=[[Viscount Gort]] |creation=1st creation |years=1975\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft |after=[[Foley Vereker, 9th Viscount Gort|Foley Vereker]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gort, Colin Vereker, 8th Viscount}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sevenoaks School]]\n[[Category:English people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Manx people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Manx people of English descent]]\n[[Category:Manx people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Manx politicians]]\n[[Category:Schuyler family]]\n[[Category:Justices of the peace]]\n", "name_user": "Place Clichy", "label": "safe", "comment": "-Category:Manx people of Dutch descent; -Category:Manx people of English descent; -Category:Manx people of Irish descentusingHotCat: although he settled in Man, his ancestry is irrelevant to this fact.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colin_Vereker,_8th_Viscount_Gort"}
{"title_page": "Ishin-denshin", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Nihongo||\u4ee5\u5fc3\u4f1d\u5fc3|'''''Ishin-denshin'''''}} is a Japanese [[idiom]]<ref name=Maynard-1993>{{cite book| last1=Maynard| first1=Michael L| last2=Maynard| first2=Senko K| author3=Taki| title=101 Japanese Idioms: Understanding Japanese Language and Culture Through Popular Phrases|url= |year=1993| publisher=McGraw Hill Professional| isbn=978-0-8442-8496-5| page=113}}</ref> which denotes a form of [[interpersonal communication]] through unspoken mutual [[understanding]]. This four-[[kanji|character]] compound (or [[yojijukugo]]) literally translates as \"what the mind thinks, the heart transmits\".  Sometimes translated into English as \"[[telepathy]]\" or \"[[sympathy]]\", ''ishin-denshin'' is also commonly rendered as \"[[Heart (symbolism)|heart]]-to-heart communication\" or \"[[Tacit knowledge|tacit understanding]]\".<ref name=\"Cheung1993\">{{cite book|last=Cheung|first=King-Kok|title=Articulate Silences: Hisaye Yamamoto, Maxine Hong Kingston, Joy Kogawa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z0DrUokTlmgC&pg=PA146|accessdate=29 July 2012|year=1993|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-8147-5|page=146}}</ref>\n\nAlthough silent understanding is generally recognized as a [[Cultural universal|universal human phenomenon]], the term ''ishin-denshin'' is often used to convey a style of [[nonverbal communication]] between two people that is felt by some Japanese to be characteristic of [[Japanese culture]].<ref name=\"DaviesIkeno2002\">{{cite book|last1=Davies|first1=Roger J. |last2=Ikeno|first2=Osamu|title=The Japanese Mind: Understanding Contemporary Japanese Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TW7lHYwXhS4C&pg=PA105|accessdate=July 28, 2012|date=March 15, 2002|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-0-8048-3295-3|pages=52\u201354, 105}}</ref> Whereas the Japanese concept of ''[[haragei]]'' denotes a deliberate form of nonverbal communication, ''ishin-denshin'' refers to a passive form of shared understanding.  ''Ishin-denshin'' is traditionally perceived by the Japanese as sincere, silent communication via the heart or belly (i.e. symbolically from the inside, ''[[Uchi-soto|uchi]]''), as distinct from overt communication via the face and mouth (the outside, ''soto''), which is seen as being more susceptible to insincerities.<ref name=\"DaviesIkeno2002\"/> The introduction of this concept to Japan (via China) is related to the traditions of [[Zen Buddhism]], where the term ''ishin-denshin'' refers to direct [[Dharma transmission|mind transmission]].<ref name=\"DaviesIkeno2002\"/><ref name=\"Baroni2002\">{{cite book|last= Baroni|first=Helen Josephine |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Zen Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=smNM4ElP3XgC&pg=PA156|accessdate=July 28, 2012|year=2002|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8239-2240-6|page=156}}</ref> [[Zen Buddhism]] tradition, in turn, draws the concept of ''ishin-denshin'' from the first [[Dharma transmission]] between [[Gautama Buddha]] and [[Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa]] in the [[Flower Sermon]].<ref name=\"Shores1998\">{{cite web |url=http://terebess.hu/zen/mesterek/JeffShore.pdf |title=THE SOURCE OF ZEN: WHO TRANSMITS WHAT? |last1=Shore |first1=Jeff |date=1998 }}</ref><ref name=\"Durix1991\">{{cite book |last=Durix |first=Claude |date=1991 |title=Cent Cl\u00e9s pour Comprendre le Zen |publisher=Le Courrier du Livre |page=43 |isbn=978-2-7029-0261-5}}</ref>\n\n''Ishin-denshin'', or non-verbal communication, continues to influence aspects of contemporary Japanese culture and [[ethics]],<ref name=\"Murata-2010\">{{cite book| last=Murata| first=K |editor=Morais da Costa |editor2=Jorge Goncalo| title=Ethical Issues and Social Dilemmas in Knowledge Management: Organizational Innovation: Organizational Innovation| chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KB1IDmxDEpkC&pg=PA10| year=2010| publisher=IGI Global |isbn=978-1-61520-874-6| page=10| chapter= Knowledge Creation and Sharing in Japanese Organisations: A Socio-Cultural Perspective on ba}}</ref> ranging from [[business practice]]s<ref name=Dougherty-1991>{{cite book| last=Dougherty| first=Andrew J |title=Japan: 2000| year=1991| publisher=Rochester Institute of Technology| page=17}}</ref> to [[end-of-life care]].<ref name=\"Slingsby2005\">{{Cite journal| last =Slingsby  | first =Brian Taylor  | title = The nature of relative subjectivity: a reflexive mode of thought | journal=The Journal of Medicine and Philosophy  |volume= 30|issue=1 |pages=9\u201325| year =2005  | pmid =15814365 |doi=10.1080/03605310590907039 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Exformation]]\n*[[Ingroups and outgroups]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Japanese social terms}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese values]]\n[[Category:Japanese words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Nihongo||\u4ee5\u5fc3\u4f1d\u5fc3|'''''Ishin-denshin'''''}} is a Japanese [[idiom]]<ref name=Maynard-1993>{{cite book| last1=Maynard| first1=Michael L| last2=Maynard| first2=Senko K| author3=Taki| title=101 Japanese Idioms: Understanding Japanese Language and Culture Through Popular Phrases|url= |year=1993| publisher=McGraw Hill Professional| isbn=978-0-8442-8496-5| page=113}}</ref> which denotes a form of [[interpersonal communication]] through unspoken mutual [[understanding]]. This four-[[kanji|character]] compound (or [[yojijukugo]]) literally translates as \"what the mind thinks, the heart transmits\".  Sometimes translated into English as \"[[telepathy]]\" or \"[[sympathy]]\", ''ishin-denshin'' is also commonly rendered as \"[[Heart (symbolism)|heart]]-to-heart communication\" or \"[[Tacit knowledge|tacit understanding]]\".<ref name=\"Cheung1993\">{{cite book|last=Cheung|first=King-Kok|title=Articulate Silences: Hisaye Yamamoto, Maxine Hong Kingston, Joy Kogawa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z0DrUokTlmgC&pg=PA146|accessdate=29 July 2012|year=1993|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-8147-5|page=146}}</ref>\n\nAlthough silent understanding is generally recognized as a universal human phenomenon, the term ''ishin-denshin'' is often used to convey a style of [[nonverbal communication]] between two people that is felt by some Japanese to be characteristic of [[Japanese culture]].<ref name=\"DaviesIkeno2002\">{{cite book|last1=Davies|first1=Roger J. |last2=Ikeno|first2=Osamu|title=The Japanese Mind: Understanding Contemporary Japanese Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TW7lHYwXhS4C&pg=PA105|accessdate=July 28, 2012|date=March 15, 2002|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-0-8048-3295-3|pages=52\u201354, 105}}</ref> Whereas the Japanese concept of ''[[haragei]]'' denotes a deliberate form of nonverbal communication, ''ishin-denshin'' refers to a passive form of shared understanding.  ''Ishin-denshin'' is traditionally perceived by the Japanese as sincere, silent communication via the heart or belly (i.e. symbolically from the inside, ''[[Uchi-soto|uchi]]''), as distinct from overt communication via the face and mouth (the outside, ''soto''), which is seen as being more susceptible to insincerities.<ref name=\"DaviesIkeno2002\"/> The introduction of this concept to Japan (via China) is related to the traditions of [[Zen Buddhism]], where the term ''ishin-denshin'' refers to direct [[Dharma transmission|mind transmission]].<ref name=\"DaviesIkeno2002\"/><ref name=\"Baroni2002\">{{cite book|last= Baroni|first=Helen Josephine |title=The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Zen Buddhism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=smNM4ElP3XgC&pg=PA156|accessdate=July 28, 2012|year=2002|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-8239-2240-6|page=156}}</ref> [[Zen Buddhism]] tradition, in turn, draws the concept of ''ishin-denshin'' from the first [[Dharma transmission]] between [[Gautama Buddha]] and [[Mah\u0101k\u0101\u015byapa]] in the [[Flower Sermon]].<ref name=\"Shores1998\">{{cite web |url=http://terebess.hu/zen/mesterek/JeffShore.pdf |title=THE SOURCE OF ZEN: WHO TRANSMITS WHAT? |last1=Shore |first1=Jeff |date=1998 }}</ref><ref name=\"Durix1991\">{{cite book |last=Durix |first=Claude |date=1991 |title=Cent Cl\u00e9s pour Comprendre le Zen |publisher=Le Courrier du Livre |page=43 |isbn=978-2-7029-0261-5}}</ref>\n\n''Ishin-denshin'', or non-verbal communication, continues to influence aspects of contemporary Japanese culture and [[ethics]],<ref name=\"Murata-2010\">{{cite book| last=Murata| first=K |editor=Morais da Costa |editor2=Jorge Goncalo| title=Ethical Issues and Social Dilemmas in Knowledge Management: Organizational Innovation: Organizational Innovation| chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KB1IDmxDEpkC&pg=PA10| year=2010| publisher=IGI Global |isbn=978-1-61520-874-6| page=10| chapter= Knowledge Creation and Sharing in Japanese Organisations: A Socio-Cultural Perspective on ba}}</ref> ranging from [[business practice]]s<ref name=Dougherty-1991>{{cite book| last=Dougherty| first=Andrew J |title=Japan: 2000| year=1991| publisher=Rochester Institute of Technology| page=17}}</ref> to [[end-of-life care]].<ref name=\"Slingsby2005\">{{Cite journal| last =Slingsby  | first =Brian Taylor  | title = The nature of relative subjectivity: a reflexive mode of thought | journal=The Journal of Medicine and Philosophy  |volume= 30|issue=1 |pages=9\u201325| year =2005  | pmid =15814365 |doi=10.1080/03605310590907039 }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Exformation]]\n*[[Ingroups and outgroups]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Japanese social terms}}\n\n[[Category:Japanese values]]\n[[Category:Japanese words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Lcscnc", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ishin-denshin"}
